      <div type="notes" xml:lang="eng">
	<p>This edition and translation is based on <ref target="bibl:Chandra1919">Chandra 1919–1920</ref>. He writes: “The sign between ka and ya in line 1 is very indistinct. Lüders takes it as nh. [I would take it as a da followe dby a ta written below the lines.—Ed.]” On <emph>abātamālā</emph> see Hultzsch in ZDMG XL, 345-346.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="edition" rend="break-none" xml:lang="pra-Latn">
	<p>
	  <lb n="1"/>
	    <gap reason="lost" quantity="unknown" unit="character"/>ka sabhariyāya <persName key="pers:Am-Cakradattā">caka<unclear>data</unclear>ya</persName> sapitukāya
	  <lb n="2"/>
	    <gap reason="lost" quantity="unknown" unit="character"/>ha<unclear>ya</unclear> sanātimitabadhavehi deyadhama
	  <lb n="3"/>
	    <gap reason="lost" quantity="unknown" unit="character"/>patiṭhapita soṭhikapaṭo abātamālā ca
	</p>
      </div>
      <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
	<p>(This) slab with svastika and an abātamālā are the pious gifts established by
	   <persName key="pers:Am-Cakradattā">Cakradattā</persName>, wife of ... ka,
	   together with her father ... and their grandsons, friends and relatives.</p>
      </div>
